The <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>’s shift toward <span style="color: #6D5298;">Christian Socialism</span> and <span style="color: #000000;">repu</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">blic</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">anism</span> has stalled with the re-election of Kuno von Westarp as party leader, promoted from his role as chairman of the Reichstag delegation. So far, Westarp has avoided drastic changes to prevent a party split, frustrating the party’s more conservative and industrial backers, who had hoped his leadership would restore the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span> to its previous course.

At the same time, Westarp is careful not to alienate the <span style="color: #6D5298;">Christian Socialist</span> wing through drastic changes to the party program, fearing a split or the defection of its working-class base back to the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD**</span>. As a compromise, he preserves some worker-friendly provisions in the party program and messaging. While this is not enough to hold onto the working-class support Lambach had built, the party offsets these losses by winning back monarchist and conservative voters from the <span style="color: #003755;">**DNF**</span>, aided by a resurgence in industrial funding.

